commit.message:
riscv32: Initial support for riscv32

This patch provides initial support on the riscv32 architecture, ply
can now be compiled and installed on riscv32 and works fine.

The implementation came from 7f9085b Initial support for riscv64, and
fix s64/u64 data type with t_sllong/t_ullong.

Change-Id: Ia5957927098543d3846f27f18bf290918bc155ed
Signed-off-by: Ism Hong <ism.hong@realtek.com>

build: Make sure all arch specific files are included in tarball

I originally overlooked this when merging the mips and riscv64 PRs.

mips: Fix access to arg registers a4-a7 on MIPS64

Access to registers a4-a7 was limited to ABI N32 use-cases, which excludes
MIPS64. Allow N32/N64 by instead excluding ABI O32 use-cases.

Signed-off-by: Tony Ambardar <Tony.Ambardar@gmail.com>

self-test: Don't rely on 'mountpoint' being universally available

Since 'mountpoint' may be missing on light-weight or embedded systems,
replace with more prevalent equivalent commands.

Signed-off-by: Tony Ambardar <Tony.Ambardar@gmail.com>

mips: Improve ABI support

- Detect ABI via compiler defines (set by -mabi=X)
- Support for mips64
- Detect SmartMIPS usage via compiler defines (set by -msmartmips)
- Support for Octeon cores

Hopefully we now have a complete definition of pt_regs without the
user having to pass extra environment options.

Import BPF headers from Linux 6.0

This way you can build ply even though your toolchain's headers may be
outdated.

self-test: Don't rely on the linker to include the script into ply

On MIPS, ld seems to tag object files created with -b binary with a
different mach than those generated by cc. Go back to basics and
convert the shell script to a C array with some good ol' od+sed
instead.

UNIX baby!

lexer.l: bugfix of incorrect line numbers

When complaining about lexer errors, the line number
is not correct if there exists multiple lines of comments
above the problematic expressions.
Reference:
    https://westes.github.io/flex/manual/How-can-I-match-C_002dstyle-comments_003f.html

arch: Add support for mips architecture

There exists mainly two variants of ABIs in the linux kernel
for MIPS architecture, o32 and n32/n64. Configure option
`CFLAGS=-DUSE_MIPS_N32 can be specified to enable n32/n64
kernel ABI.
Note that only support for 32-bit MIPS architecture is added.
changelog: Update for 2.3.0
README: Document the support for riscv64

test: Disable CI testing until newer toolchains are in place

This is just temporary of course.

...@RemindMe_OfThis in 10 years

riscv64: Initial support for riscv64

This patch provides initial support on the riscv64 architecture, ply
can now be compiled and installed on riscv64 and works fine.
Fix issue #81 .

Signed-off-by: Mingzheng Xing xingmingzheng@iscas.ac.cn

ply: Replace BEGIN/END implementation with bpf_prog_test_run

Before we used uprobe to implement BEGIN/END, which required complex
offset calculations, we can use bpf_prog_test_run to replace it.
In addition, this commit solves the bug mentioned in the issue #83 ,
so that BEGIN/END can work correctly.

Signed-off-by: Mingzheng Xing xingmingzheng@iscas.ac.cn

ply: Use new read_kernel variants

In order to eliminate possible compatibility issues, we should
update probe_read[_str] to the probe_read_kernel[_str] variants.
Note that this requires linux kernel version 5.5 and above.

Signed-off-by: Mingzheng Xing xingmingzheng@iscas.ac.cn

test: Improve interactive use of tests

Use phony targets to trigger rebuild and install of ply on each
invokation. Make sure that mksquashfs replaces files in an updated
archive, rather than the quaint (default!?) option of creating new
index suffixed directories.

With this you can now:

10 make zero-shell
20 # test something
30 # modify source
40 goto 10
changelog: Update for 2.2.0

Merge pull request #78 from namhyung/misc-fix

Small touch-up of the error message.

bultin-in: Show proper error message for maps

Sometimes I mistakenly type '$' instead of '@' for maps.  But the
error message was not clear and just showed an assertion failure.
Check the type of the node when it assignes to a map like below:

  # ply 'kr:vfs_read { $r["bytes"] = quantize(retval); }'
  <input>:1:14-25: error: expect map type, but get $r
  ERR:-22

isstring: Fix off-by-one

Previously, an array of size 4 with the following content:

74 65 73 74

Would be classified as a string ("test"). In fact, it is not as there
is no space to store the NUL. This would sometimes lead to weird
trailing output on truncated strings.

Ensure that the NUL byte also fits inside the string. Notably, this
also means that truncated strings will be output as hexdumps, which
makes it obvious that the truncation occurred.

tracepoint: Support dynamic tracepoint data

Fields marked with the "__data_loc" attribute are pointers to dynamic
data stored after the fixed fields.

Provide what is essentially a specialized version of "mem()", called
"dyn()", which operates on such a pointer grabs a copy of the data.

tracepoint: Source field offsets from format file, fixes iovisor/ply#75

Since offsets are now stored in the field, rather than being
calculated, use the information provided by the kernel about how each
field is laid out in memory.

type: Allow non-standard struct layouts

Some tracepoint data uses a layout that is neither packed nor
"regular". The actual offset is available in the tracepoint's "format"
description, but ply has not been able to make use of it.

This is a first step towards changing that. Store the offset of each
field rather than computing it. This means we can just copy whatever
the format says. It also makes it easier to import types from BTF and
DWARF in the future.

man: Improve layout of tracepoint section

Still not quite right, but better. TODO: Move to mandoc.

provider: Fix a complier warning

  CC       provider/libply_la-special.lo
provider/special.c: In function register_special_probes:
provider/special.c:67:34: warning: base_addr may be used uninitialized
                                   in this function [-Wmaybe-uninitialized]
   67 |  end_offset = (unsigned long)end - base_addr;
      |               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^~~~~~~~~~~

provider: add 'interval' provider

The interval provider is to trigger some actions periodically.
Usually it can be used to print maps/aggregations and clear.
The syntax is "interval:TIME[UNIT]".  The default unit is second
if omitted.

For example, the following will show the histogram of read size in
every second.

  # cat readhist.ply
  kretprobe:vfs_read { @r["size"] = quantize(retval); }
  interval:1 { print(@r); clear(@r); }

  # ply readhist.ply

aux: add perf_event_attach_raw() function

The perf_event_attach_raw() does similar to perf_event_attach() but it
allows to pass raw event info like type, config and period.  This will
be used to create custom event like in the interval timer.

built-in: add 'clear' function

The clear function takes 1 argument (map or aggregation) and remove
all elements in it.

built-in: Support printing maps in print()

Rewrite map symbols to map references and print them like below:

  $ cat readsize.ply
  kr:vfs_read { @["bytes"] = quantize(retval); }
  END { print(@); }    # here!

  $ sudo ply -c 'sleep 1' readsize.ply

libply: export ply_map_print()

This function is to print a single map given in the 'sym' argument to
a file pointed by 'fp'.  Also change to call type_fprint() for each
key and value types separately.
